2026-06-10 17:22:38,404 DEBUG Tool result: ToolCallRecord(
    tool_call=ToolCall(
        id='call_adef317fd6fb48a7a8442623',
        call_id=None,
        name='retrieve_information',
        args='{"prompt": "What specific language does the filing use regarding V3 satellite deployment timing? Look for statements about when V3 satellites (also called Starlink V3 or next-generation satellites) will begin launching or be deployed. Include any qualifiers, target dates, or risk language. Retrieve from {{spacex_s1}}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'What specific language does the filing use regarding V3 satellite deployment timing? Look for statements about when V3 satellites (also called Starlink V3 or next-generation satellites) will begin launching or be deployed. Include any qualifiers, target dates, or risk language. Retrieve from {{spacex_s1}}'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# V3 Satellite Deployment Timing: Specific Filing Language\n\n## Target Date Statements\n\nThe filing contains a consistent deployment target, repeated across multiple sections:\n\n> **"We expect to commence deploying our next-generation V3 satellites, designed to offer one Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite, using Starship in the second half of 2026."**\n\nThis identical phrasing appears in the Prospectus Summary, two separate Preamble business overview sections, and the Starlink Consumer Broadband discussion.\n\nA slightly more detailed version appears in the growth strategy section:\n\n> **"For our Starlink broadband constellation, we will continue deployment of more of our V2 Mini satellites, and in the second half of 2026, we expect to begin deployment of our next-generation V3 satellites, each of which is designed to offer one Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite."**\n\nAnd in the definitions section:\n\n> **"\'V3 satellites\' refers to our next-generation Starlink broadband satellites, which are designed to offer one Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite and which we expect to begin deploying on Starship in the second half of 2026."**\n\n## Key Qualifiers\n\n- **"expect to"** — appears in every deployment date statement; signals projection rather than commitment\n- **"using Starship"** — the V3 deployment date is explicitly conditioned on Starship capability\n- **"designed to offer"** — the 1 Tbps capacity figure is a design target, not a demonstrated capability\n- **"expect to begin deploying"** — emphasizes *commencement* only; no completion date given\n- **"a single Starship launch will be capable of deploying up to 60 V3 satellites"** — "up to" and "capable of" are hedging language\n- **"a potential twenty-fold increase"** — "potential" qualifies the capacity improvement claim\n\n## Critical Dependencies Noted in the Filing\n\nThe filing repeatedly ties V3 deployment to Starship readiness:\n\n> **"Our current operational rockets, including Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy, are not capable of deploying V3 satellites and V2 Mobile satellites."**\n\nThis means there is no fallback launch vehicle. The filing also notes:\n\n> **"Full reusability of Starship\'s upper stage is not required to deploy our V3 satellites and V2 Mobile satellites in low-Earth orbit. In-orbit refueling is also not required for any of these LEO programs."**\n\nThis is a notable *de-risking* statement — it clarifies that near-term V3 deployment does not require the most ambitious Starship milestones to be met.\n\n## Risk Language\n\nThe risk disclosures contain the most extensive qualifiers:\n\n> **"If we are unable to successfully complete the development, testing, and deployment of Starship at scale in accordance with our anticipated schedule, or at all, or if we are unable to achieve sufficient launch cadence, reusability, and capability, our ability to execute our growth strategy (such as the deployment of our next-generation V3 satellites, V2 satellite-to-mobile connectivity, and providing orbital AI compute infrastructure) would be materially and adversely affected."**\n\n> **"Any significant delay in achieving key development milestones, obtaining the necessary regulatory approvals or increasing and maintaining our launch cadence, reusability, and capability would impede the expansion of our service offerings, defer anticipated revenue streams, and negatively impact our growth trajectory and competitive positioning in rapidly evolving markets."**\n\n> **"If we are unable to achieve the commercial development, anticipated performance, launch cadence, or cost efficiencies associated with Starship within expected timeframes, our ability to deploy next-generation V3 satellites, V2 Mobile satellites, and orbital AI compute infrastructure at scale, reduce capital and operating costs (including cost per token), realize projected revenue growth, and retain existing customers from these initiatives could be materially and adversely affected. This includes our expectations with respect to completion of flight testing of Starship and commencement of payload delivery to orbit."**\n\nThe filing also enumerates specific risk factors that could cause delay:\n\n> **"Delays or challenges in the Starship program have in the past occurred, and may occur in the future due to a variety of factors, including unforeseen technical challenges, supply chain disruptions, manufacturing difficulties, delays in the development, construction or commissioning of launch and fueling infrastructure (such as launch pads, air separation units and other propellant production systems), unavailability of such launch and fueling infrastructure (including launch pads) in sufficient number and in operable condition (including as a result of mishaps), loss or damage to the vehicle or other components, regulatory hurdles, or the need for additional design modifications."**\n\nAnd a general market-level caveat:\n\n> **"the size and growth of our various existing and future markets… particularly emerging or unproven markets that may not materialize as expected or on anticipated timelines"**\n\n## Related Timeline: Starship Payload Delivery to Orbit\n\nV3 deployment depends on Starship achieving orbit-class cargo delivery. The filing states:\n\n> **"We expect Starship to commence payload delivery to orbit in the second half of 2026."**\n\nThis matches the V3 deployment window, indicating that the first V3 launches are expected to be among the earliest Starship commercial payload missions.\n\n## Orbital AI Compute Satellite Reference\n\nThe filing also notes a separate but related satellite program built on the V3 platform:\n\n> **"We expect to begin deploying our orbital AI compute satellites as early as 2028."**\n\nThis uses "as early as" — a softer qualifier than the V3 broadband language, suggesting greater timeline uncertainty for this derivative program.\n\n## Summary of Language Patterns\n\n| Element | Language Used |\n|---|---|\n| **Deployment start** | "expect to commence deploying" / "expect to begin deploying" |\n| **Target window** | "in the second half of 2026" |\n| **Capacity per satellite** | "designed to offer one Tbps" |\n| **Launch vehicle** | "using Starship" — no fallback to Falcon |\n| **Per-launch capacity** | "capable of deploying up to 60 V3 satellites" |\n| **Capacity improvement** | "a potential twenty-fold increase" |\n| **Cost reduction** | "nine times" total reduction from V1 to V3 |\n| **Risk qualifier** | "would be materially and adversely affected" if Starship delays occur |\n| **Past precedent** | "Delays or challenges… have in the past occurred, and may occur in the future" |\n\nThe filing uses consistent hedging — every deployment date is an "expect," every capacity figure is "designed to" or "up to," and the risk section is explicit that the entire V3 program is dependent on a Starship program that has not yet completed flight testing or begun commercial payload delivery.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=29.71,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
