        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'What specific language does the filing use regarding V2 Mobile deployment timing? Look for statements about when V2 Mobile (Starlink V2 Mobile, direct-to-cell, or mobile satellite service) will begin operating or be deployed. Include any qualifiers, target dates, or risk language. Retrieve from {{spacex_s1}}'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# V2 Mobile Deployment Timing: Specific Filing Language\n\n## Primary Target Date\n\nThe filing states a **single target year for satellite deployment**, with no quarter specified:\n\n> **"We plan to expand our mobile constellation by deploying our next-generation mobile V2 Mobile satellites in 2027"**\n\nThe definitions section reaffirms this:\n\n> **"\'V2 Mobile satellites\' refers to our next-generation mobile satellites, which are designed to provide more comprehensive satellite-to-mobile services, including broadband data and IoT connectivity and which we expect to begin deploying on Starship in 2027."**\n\n**Key observation:** The filing says satellites will *begin deploying* in 2027—it does **not** state when commercial service (Gen2) will *commence*. The deployment date and service launch date are treated as separate, and no service launch date is given.\n\n---\n\n## Prerequisites Before Commercial Service Can Begin\n\nThe filing is explicit that deployment ≠ service launch. Three prerequisites are listed:\n\n### 1. U.S. Regulatory Authorizations\n> "the FCC approved the EchoStar license transfer in May 2026, and we separately expect to receive the remaining necessary U.S. regulatory authorizations in the second or third quarter of 2026."\n\n**Qualifying language:** "expect to receive" (not "will receive").\n\n### 2. V2 Mobile Satellites in Orbit\n> "we still require our V2 Mobile satellites to be in orbit"\n\n### 3. EchoStar Spectrum Acquisition Completion\n> "[we] must complete the acquisition of the relevant spectrum from EchoStar before we can commence our planned commercial Gen2 service in the United States."\n\n### 4. International Approvals\n> "Internationally, we have filed applications in nearly every country in which we intend to operate our Gen2 service, and approvals have been granted in a limited number of these jurisdictions to date. Each international jurisdiction presents its own regulatory process and timeline, and **we cannot predict when or whether approvals will be granted in any given market.**"\n\n---\n\n## Starship Dependency (Critical Risk)\n\nThe filing draws an explicit, repeated dependency between V2 Mobile deployment and Starship:\n\n> "Our ability to execute our growth strategy is highly dependent on Starship. If we are unable to achieve the commercial development, anticipated performance, launch cadence, or cost efficiencies associated with Starship **within expected timeframes**, our ability to deploy next-generation V3 satellites, **V2 Mobile satellites**, and orbital AI compute infrastructure at scale, reduce capital and operating costs (including cost per token), **realize projected revenue growth**, and retain existing customers from these initiatives **could be materially and adversely affected.**"\n\n> "**Our current operational rockets, including Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy, are not capable of deploying V3 satellites and V2 Mobile satellites.**"\n\n> "Achieving our targeted launch cadence with Starship will require significant progress on several key milestones and the investment of significant capital resources."\n\n**No Starship-to-orbit date is given for payload missions**, only that development must "commence" with no date provided.\n\n---\n\n## 5G Compliance Risk (Qualifying Language)\n\nEven once satellites are in orbit and spectrum is acquired, the filing flags a technology dependency:\n\n> "achieving full 5G NR-NTN compliance and optimal performance would likely require handset manufacturers to implement hardware and software modifications… There can be no assurance that these modifications will be adopted on our preferred timeline, or at all."\n\n> "Internationally, we face similar constraints"\n\n---\n\n## ITU Coordination Timeline\n\n> "We have an operational coordination agreement with EchoStar, which we expect to continue through 2026 and 2027"\n\nThis implies spectrum coordination work extends through the entirety of the 2027 deployment window.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Risk Language and Qualifiers\n\n| Element | Language Used | Confidence Level |\n|---|---|---|\n| V2 Mobile satellite deployment | "plan to deploy… in 2027" | Plan / intent |\n| U.S. remaining regulatory approvals | "expect to receive" in Q2/Q3 2026 | Expectation |\n| International regulatory approvals | "cannot predict when or whether" | Unpredictable |\n| Spectrum acquisition from EchoStar | Must be completed before service | Prerequisite (not timed) |\n| Starship readiness | Dependent on milestones with no date | Unspecified |\n| 5G handset compatibility | "no assurance… on our preferred timeline, or at all" | Uncertain |\n| Commercial Gen2 service launch | **No date given** | Not stated |\n\n**Bottom line:** The filing commits only to **beginning V2 Mobile satellite deployment in 2027** as a plan, while identifying at least five material prerequisites—Starship operational readiness, satellite in-orbit status, EchoStar spectrum completion, U.S. regulatory clearance (expected Q2/Q3 2026), and international approvals (undated)—none of which carry firm guarantees. No date is provided for when commercial Gen2 service will actually begin.',
