e programs depend on Starship. V2 Mobile depends additionally on regulatory and spectrum outcomes outside SpaceX\'s control. This means V2 Mobile risk is *compounded* — it faces Starship risk *plus* exogenous risks.\\n\\n5. **Absence of disclosure is itself material.** The filing does not provide: (a) a Starship commercial service ramp schedule; (b) a V3 deployment completion date or volume target; (c) any date for V2 Mobile commercial service launch. The consistent omission of completion/commercialization dates suggests management is either unable or unwilling to provide end-to-end timelines for these programs.\\n\\n6. **Past delays are cited as precedent.** The filing\'s explicit acknowledgment that Starship delays \\"have in the past occurred\\" and that rocket programs \\"have historically required substantial time and resources\\" establishes a disclosed pattern that, combined with the ambitious H2 2026 targets, elevates the probability assessment for timeline slippage.\\n\\n7. **The de-risking language on reusability/refueling is strategically significant.** By explicitly stating that full upper-stage reusability and in-orbit refueling are not required for LEO programs, the filing attempts to insulate V3 and V2 Mobile deployment timelines from the most technically ambitious Starship milestones. This suggests awareness that those milestones carry higher risk and an effort to decouple near-term satellite deployment from long-term Starship goals.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Sources\\n\\n- SpaceX S-1 filing (May 20, 2026): https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm"}',
